sentence: Here's your weekly Investing Action Plan: what you need to know as an investor for the coming day.

The strength of China's internet economy will come into focus with quarterly reports coming up from big names like Tencent ( TCEHY ) and Alibaba ( BABA )-rival JD.com ( JD ), while America's retail sector will get a status report ahead of the crucial holiday shopping season with reports from Wal-Mart ( WMT ), Home Depot ( HD ) and Best Buy (BBY).
Investors will also hear what General Electric 's (GE) future will look like when the industrial conglomerate's new CEO gives a highly anticipated presentation.
With Bitcoin up more than 600% this year, here are five related stocks to watch: Nvidia (NVDA), AMD (AMD), Goldman Sachs (GS), CME Group (CME) and CBOE Global Markets (CBOE).
Graphics processors from Nvidia and AMD are used to vet and clear cryptocurrency transactions.
By clearing Bitcoin transactions, "miners" create more of the cryptocoins.
While both have noted signs of weaker sales for their crypto-related products recently, demand can also be volatile.

Shares of Nvidia jumped 5.3% to close at 216.14 on the stock market today , after delivering strong Q3 earnings and guidance late Thursday , putting shares well into profit-taking sell territory

AMD, which plans to join forces with Intel to compete against Nvidia in laptop gaming chips, rose 1.3% to 11.26.
Goldman Sachs edged down 0.3% to 240.15, but is still near a 247.17 buy point in a cup-with-handle base.
The Wall Street Journal reported last month that Goldman is considering developing a cryptocurrency trading operation.
CME Group rose 0.5% to 137.88, extended from a 128.06 buy point.
Late last month, the exchange operator said it would launch Bitcoin futures before year-end.
The decision came amid "increasing client interest in the evolving cryptocurrency markets," the derivatives marketplace said in a statement announcing the launch.
The Chicago Board of Options Exchange has also said it plans to launch Bitcoin futures in Q4 or early 2018.
CBOE shares edged up 0.3% to 114.45, far extended from a 81.46 entry of a base-on-base pattern cleared in April.
E-commerce company JD.com leads the list of five China internet leaders reporting earnings.
JD is the largest of the bunch with the consensus on EPS at 10 cents, vs. 3 cents a year ago, on revenue of $12.25 billion, up 36%.
JD.com reports before the market open Monday, as does 58.com (WUBA), called the Craigslist of China.
The consensus looks for EPS of 8 cents, vs. a 1-cent per share loss, on a 26% jump in revenue to $387.7 million.
Social media company YY (YY) reports after the market close Tuesday, with EPS seen up 35% to $1.45 and revenue expected to rise 35% to $423 million.
Internet messaging giant Tencent Holdings reports early Wednesday, and the consensus on EPS is 26 cents, up 37%, on revenue growth of 56% to $9.39 billion.
Video game developer NetEase (NTES) reports late Wednesday, and the outlook on EPS is $2.86, down 16%, on 37% revenue growth to $1.89 billion.

Here's What To Expect When China Internet Giant JD.com Reports Earnings

When Target (TGT) reports Wednesday, Wall Street is looking for an 18% EPS drop to 85 cents on a 0.5% sales rise to $16.52 billion.
The big-box chain has scored with new private-label offerings lately, giving it more exclusivity vs. rivals.
Wal-Mart's Thursday report is expected to bring a 1% EPS dip to 97 cents on a more than 2% revenue increase to $121.02 billion.
A flurry of recent e-commerce deals have the retail giant positioned as a major online player too.
The retailers are each battling Amazon.com (AMZN) and have rolled out free-shipping deals lately as shoppers start looking for holiday gifts.
Off-price chain TJX (TJX) reports Tuesday and EPS is seen rising 10% to $1 as revenue grows 7% to $8.89 billion.
Peer Ross Stores (ROST), which reports Thursday, is seen growing EPS by 8% to 67 cents, on 6% sales gains to $3.27 billion.
Among other retailers: Gap (GPS) is up to bat on Thursday, and Hibbett Sports (HIBB) and Foot Locker (FL) report Friday.
IBD'S TAKE:Buying or holding a stock can be risky heading into an earnings report.
Here's anearnings options strategythat can help you cash in on post-earnings stock gains, while minimizing the risk from a weak quarter.
Best Buy reports Q3 earnings on Thursday.
Wall Street expects EPS of 79 cents, up 27%, on revenue of $9.35 billion, up 4.6%.
The consumer-electronics retailer faces doubts about its sales-growth targets and is grappling with the same problems from e-commerce that all retailers face.
But analysts say the chain's support services - like its Geek Squad and In-Home Advisor programs - could distance it from the retail death spiral.
They also say Best Buy, which sees appliances as a growth opportunity, would benefit from Sears ' (SHLD) decision to stop selling Whirlpool (WHR) products.

The home-improvement giant, set to release earnings before the open on Tuesday, is expected to report a 13% EPS increase to $1.81, and revenue is seen rising 5.6% to $24.45 billion, as hurricane recovery added to already robust demand from the housing sector.
The upper range of estimates has revenue topping $25 billion, which would be its strongest growth in more than a year.

Home Depot shares are in buy range, after initially clearing a 160.96 buy point in September, but sold off somewhat recently amid concern that Republican proposals to scale back or eliminate the deduction for state and local taxes, including property taxes, and high-value mortgages would weaken the housing market.

GE To Lay Out New Strategy, Dividend Plans

On Monday, new CEO John Flannery is set to announce sweeping changes at the storied industrial giant, which is facing a cash crunch and meager profits.
Flannery has promised deep asset and cost cuts.
He is likely to slash GE's prized high dividends to fund a new turnaround strategy.
But even those moves may not be bold enough to satisfy restless investors.
Some analysts say GE has no business paying a dividend at all.
Others have called for a breakup of the conglomerate.
Meanwhile, the stock hovers near 20, its lowest level in years.

As GE's Moment Of Truth Nears, Look For Answers To These 4 Questions

Chip-gear maker Applied Materials (AMAT) is scheduled to report fiscal Q4 results after the market close on Thursday.
Analysts expect the Santa Clara, Calif.-based company to earn 91 cents a share, up 38% year over year, on sales of $3.94 billion, up 20%, in the quarter ended Oct. 29.
The company has benefited from strong chip production trends as well as growth in manufacturing OLED displays.
Shares have soared 75% this year, making it one of the best-performing stocks in an already hot Electronic-Semiconductor Equipment industry group.
The biannual show will run Sunday through Thursday and will feature jets from Boeing (BA), Airbus (EADSY) and Lockheed Martin (LMT).
Analysts expect a muted event this year amid still-low oil prices and regional political tensions with Qatar.
One potential order to watch is a 20-plane deal for Airbus' A380 from Emirates, which could determine how much longer the superjumbo jet stays in production, though any delivery timeline will be key.
Business jet orders could be big at the show as cheap fuel boosted private air travel.
Demand for weapons is on the rise in the region, especially for precision munitions and missile defense systems.

What To Expect From Boeing, Airbus, Lockheed At The Dubai Airshow

After the close Wednesday, analysts expect the computer networking giant's fiscal Q1 EPS to fall 1% to 60 cents, with sales sliding 2% to $12.11 billion.
Cisco Systems (CSCO) has stepped up acquisitions, most recently BroadSoft and AppDynamics, to shift to software and services from its core business of selling network switches and routers.
Hopes for corporate tax reform could boost the dividend-paying stock.

This Cloud Company Took On Cisco And Citrix, Now Eyes Salesforce

Late Wednesday, analysts expect the data management systems giant to report fiscal Q2 EPS growth of 15% to 69 cents, with revenue rising 3.2% to $1.38 billion.
NetApp (NTAP) in August reported fiscal Q1 earnings and revenue above views, but its September-quarter guidance was light.
Analysts have been expecting stiffer competition from Dell Technologies (DVMT).
NetApp shares are in buy range.
The data analytics software provider reports Q3 results after the market close Thursday.
The consensus on EPS is 14 cents, up 17%, on revenue growth of 27% to $310 million.
Needham recently initiated coverage on Splunk (SPLK) with a buy rating and price target of 95, a premium of more than 30%, saying Splunk is an industry leader with strong products.
Shares broke out over the past week and are holding just above a 69.71 entry.

On Tuesday, the National Federation of Independent Business releases its small business confidence gauge, following GOP tax plans that the trade group initially opposed before changes were made that won its support.
On Wednesday, reports on consumer inflation, retail sales and New York Fed-region manufacturing come out.
On Thursday, data on Philly Fed-region business activity, industrial production, import and export prices, and homebuilder confidence are due.
On Friday, reports on housing starts and e-commerce retail sales are coming.
